<p class="article-lead">Perfume fragrance families give a brand and perfumer a shared starting vocabulary, but they should not become rigid boxes.</p><p>Citrus and aromatic directions can communicate brightness; floral structures range from transparent to opulent; woody styles may feel dry, creamy or smoky; amber directions often emphasize warmth and resins; gourmand ideas use edible associations; chypre and fougère describe recognizable structural traditions.</p><h2>Use families with contrasts</h2><p>“Woody” becomes useful when paired with choices such as clean versus smoky, dry versus sweet, intimate versus projecting. Add the customer, occasion, disliked notes and desired dry-down. References should explain an aspect, not demand an exact duplicate.</p><p>The brief should leave enough space for creative interpretation while making it possible to explain why one sample fits better than another.</p>
